4.54/5  rDev +1.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5TmKeisySC, Apr 04, 2016
4.38/5  rDev -1.8%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.25Gregf51, Apr 04, 2016
4.33/5  rDev -2.9%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.2522oz bottle courtesy of the largesse of @Ri0. I’d never heard of this particular beer before, or what is presumably the XHops series, but it’s a great day for this style of beer.
Poured into a Sierra Nevada pint glass, this is a chill-hazed golden amber color, with a big, pillowy white head that hung around for a bit and left lots of lace on the sides of said glass.
There’s a tropical fruit,  juicy hop aroma to this. More than anything else it reminds me of pineapple juice. Amped up pretty high for an APA, too. I’ve had numerous IPAs with less hop aroma.
The taste roughly follows the nose. Juicyfruit, definitely, but more complex. I get some piney and grapefruity notes as well. There’s not a whole lot of bitterness, but just enough to keep things from being cloying. Things end with a lightly dry, fairly crisp finish for all that sweet, tropical fruitiness. 
The body lies somewhere between light and medium, and despite it’s modestly crisp finish, the mouthfeel is as stickily resiny as many an IPA. Definitely a style straddle, and not just in terms of mouthfeel.
Weird. Describe this beer to me, I might not be that excited, but it’s awesome. I don’t know what the abv is (haven’t looked it up yet), but it doesn’t seem like much. This is a juicy APA that is punching above it’s weight in the flavor and drinkability department. I would enthusiastically cast my vote for this, were it running for President. Great stuff, @Ri0! 1,466 characterswoemad, Apr 03, 2016
4.08/5  rDev -8.5%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4CTFalcon, Apr 03, 2016
4.46/5  rDev 0%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5Fresh 22oz. bomber bottle poured into my trusty favorite snifter.
Look: Golden, orange hue, foamy head settles into faint ring around the glass. Some floating foam islands and sticky lacing.  Careful pour still yielded some hop floaties, which I don't have a problem with.
Smell: This smells like a TG hoppy beer.  They seem to all have a similar aroma profile at least IMO.  Good thing it is a pretty great aroma profile!  Citrus is up front, specifically zest of lemon, not a juicy smell, but more of a refreshing spritz of lemony goodness.  Some grassy scents, fresh cut first run hay from early summer wafting over the fields.
Taste: Similar to the nose.  Big, crisp, biting hop flavor.  Lemon zest and earthy dankness.  Refined and biting on the tongue, doesn't linger and doesn't offend.  This is a pale ale after all, can't go to overboard.
Feel: Somewhat effervescent, light, bubbly, crisp and goes down easy.
Overall: Worthy of its rating, sits at a bit higher class then the other XHOPS offerings from TG, rightly so being gold, the king of metals.  All of their brews are interesting, they are different than what I am used to with the local New England juice bombs, but are often equally great. 1,211 charactersjhavs, Apr 03, 2016
